<Title>Tailwind</Title>

For those looking to use Tailwind CSS with the Burrito Design System, we provide a Tailwind v4 theme file that uses Burritos design tokens. This allows you to leverage the power of Tailwind while maintaining the design consistency and components provided by Burrito.

<blockquote className="callout">
  <span aria-hidden="true">📣</span>  <strong>Note:</strong> We are currently only providing support for `tailwind@4.x.x`. If you are still using v3, please refer to [Tailwind's migration guide](https://tailwindcss.com/docs/upgrade-guide) to get upgraded.
</blockquote>

## Setup

Import Tailwind and the Burrito theme files in your main CSS file:

```css
/* ./src/index.css */

@import 'tailwindcss';
@import '@janeapp/burrito-design-system/tailwind/v4/theme.css';

/* Other custom styles below */
```

Then import the Burrito and tailwind styles into your app entrypoint (e.g., `App.tsx`) and wrap your app in the `BurritoProvider`:

```tsx
// ./src/App.tsx
import React from 'react';
import { BurritoProvider } from '@janeapp/burrito-design-system';

// Import Burrito fonts
import '@janeapp/burrito-design-system/fonts.css';
// Import Burrito global theme with design token variables
import '@janeapp/burrito-design-system/globalTheme';
// Import your main CSS file with Tailwind and Burrito theme
import './index.css';

function App() {
  return (
    <BurritoProvider>
      {/* Your app components */}
    </BurritoProvider>
  );
}
```

## Usage

Now that your app is setup with a Burrito themed Tailwind, you can start using tailwind utility classes as you normally would.

If you're unfamiliar with Tailwind, check out the [Tailwind documentation](https://tailwindcss.com/docs) for more information on how to use it.

### Colors

If you wanted to use the `brand-80` color token from Burrito, you can use:

- `bg-brand-80` for background color
- `text-brand-80` for text color
- `border-brand-80` for border color

### Spacing

You can use the Burrito spacing tokens in Tailwind as well. For example, to apply a margin of `sizing-4x`, you can use:

- `m-4` for 4x spacing margin on all sides
- `mx-4` for 4x spacing margin on the x-axis (left and right)
- `my-4` for 4x spacing margin on the y-axis (top and bottom)
- `mt-4` for 4x spacing margin on the top
- `mb-4` for 4x spacing margin on the bottom
- `ml-4` for 4x spacing margin on the left
- `mr-4` for 4x spacing margin on the right

The same also applies to padding, width, height, and other spacing-related utilities.

## What is not available?

While Burrito provides a comprehensive set of design tokens and components, there are some that have been intentionally left out of the Tailwind theme. This is to encourage developers to use the provided Burrito components before resulting to using Tailwind classes.

### Typography

Currently, while you can access typography tokens through Tailwind, the font sizes are not linked to their respective line-height and tracking values.
This is because Burrito already exposes through the `<Text />` component the correct font size, line-height, and tracking values for each text size in the scale.
